UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105033075659?origin=resultslist
AB  - Accurate charging load forecasting at charging stations (CSs) is crucial for alleviating the impacts of large-scale electric vehicle (EV) integration on power grids. However, existing centralized forecasting methods rely on data sharing among CSs and EVs, which raises serious privacy and data leakage concerns. To overcome these limitations, this paper proposes a stable and efficient fully decentralized blockchain-assisted federated learning (FL) approach for CS load forecasting, ensuring data privacy and security. First, a privacy-preserving FL-based forecasting framework is developed, in which CSs collaboratively train a global model by exchanging model parameters instead of raw data. Each CS adopts a hybrid deep learning model that combines a Temporal Convolutional Network (TCN) and a Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) network to capture both local temporal patterns and long-term dependencies in charging load data, while maintaining low communication overhead and high parallelism. Second, to eliminate the single point of failure associated with centralized servers, a blockchain-based distributed aggregation mechanism is designed, where model aggregation tasks are dynamically assigned to a subset of CSs in each training round. Moreover, a model verification algorithm is introduced to identify and discard low-quality or malicious updates, thereby mitigating poisoning attacks, and enhancing system robustness and security further. Finally, extensive experiments demonstrate that the proposed method achieves superior forecasting accuracy and robust performance under various conditions, while effectively preserving the privacy and security of CS load data. © 2026
