AB  - Vehicle-to-Vehicle (V2V) energy trading introduces a novel approach for Electric Vehicles (EVs) to engage in direct power exchange. This peer-to-peer energy-sharing model significantly enhances energy efficiency by allowing EVs with surplus charge to supply power to others, which is particularly advantageous during long journeys or in areas with limited charging infrastructure. V2V energy trading alleviates the pressure on public charging stations, optimizes energy distribution among vehicles, and diminishes grid demand during peak periods. Moreover, it is pivotal to the evolution of decentralized energy markets and the progression of smart grids, thereby facilitating the integration of renewable energy sources into the transportation sector. However, challenges persist in the practical implementation of V2V energy trading systems. The lack of standardized trading protocols hinders effective energy transactions among different EVs, leading to interoperability issues. Furthermore, the need for real-time data exchange exposes the system to cyber threats and data breaches, raising security and privacy concerns. To address these issues, this paper introduces a blockchain-based V2V energy trading system prototype that utilizes EVs as mobile energy storage units. It employs a decentralized trading protocol for secure transactions and presents a Deep Reinforcement Learning (DRL)-based optimization model for dynamic trading matches, alongside a scalable blockchain prototype featuring a sharding consensus mechanism, demonstrating robust performance through empirical testing. © 2002-2012 IEEE.
