AB  - Digital twins have become formidable systems of real-time control and optimization of urban infrastructures, but the conventional centralized versions are subject to critical bottlenecks of data, overheads of power consumption, and susceptibility to cyber-physical attacks. The proposed framework in this paper is Energy-Efficient Decentralized Digital Twin (E2-DTwin) which incorporates IoT-based sensing, blockchain-based data reconciliation, and Graph Neural Network (GNN)-based spatiotemporal modeling to support self-optimizing city energy management. The E2-DTwin contrasts traditional centralized technologies and implements intelligence sharing among networked farms of photovoltaic microgrids and EV chargers and water-energy nexus without interventions on the blockchain through which the decentralized twin versions are synchronized. The GNN module learns how the assets of the city have interdependence with each other to anticipate anomalies and preemptively control operations. Simulation of the proposed system on the Hyperledger Besu and MATLAB Simscape platform shows that the system is associated with higher accuracy in anomaly detection (31.5 %) and faster decision magnification (26.8 %) and reduced overhead on its synchronization (18.9 %) than the centralized baselines. Such results underscore the novelty of the framework to combine decentralized trust, predictive intelligence, and energy efficiency and lead to cyber-resilient, sustainable, and autonomous infrastructures of smart cities. © 2026
